plot: Generic X-Y Plotting

plot() function in R Programming Language is defined as a generic function for plotting. It can be used to create basic graphs of a different type.

  • Syntax: plot(x, y, type)

  • Parameters

  • x and y: coordinates of points to plot

  • type: the type of graph to create

x=seq(-2,2,0.001)
y1=exp(x)
plot(x,y1,type="l")

Use lwd to change thickness of a line

Use lty to change types of line

Use xlab , ylab to write text on the axes

Use col to use color of your choice.

Use xlim, ylim to set axes limits.

Use main to write title of the plot.

plot(x,y1,type="l",lwd=2,lty=4,xlab="name of x variable", ylab="name of y variable", col="purple", main="...plot of ...", xlim=c(-2,2),ylim=c(0,10))
#use lines to add more plots
y2=exp(-1*x)
lines(x,y2, col="blue",lty=3,lwd=3)
#use legend to define the plots
legend("topright",legend=c("line 1","line 2"),col=c("purple","blue"),lty=c(4,3),lwd=c(2,3),text.font = 2,cex= 0.5,title = "line types")

bty in R

The bty option in the R plot() function controls the box style of base.

  • o: complete box (default parameter)

  • n: no box

  • 7: top + right

  • L: bottom + left

  • C: top + left + bottom

  • U: left + bottom + right

x=seq(-2,2,0.001)
y1=exp(x)
y2=exp(-1*x)
plot(x,y1,type="l",lwd=2,lty=4,xlab="name of x variable", ylab="name of y variable", col="purple", main="...plot of ...", xlim=c(-2,2),ylim=c(0,10),bty="n")

ggplot

  • Next we will learn how to visualise your data using ggplot2.

  • R has several systems for making graphs, but ggplot2 is one of the most elegant and most versatile.

  • ggplot2 implements the grammar of graphics, a coherent system for describing and building graphs.

  • With ggplot2, you can do more faster by learning one system and applying it in many places.

  • ggplot2 comes with many geom functions that each add a different type of layer to a plot.

  • Each geom function in ggplot2 takes a mapping argument . This defines how variables in our data set are mapped to visual properties.

  • The mapping argument is always paired with aes() , and the x and y arguments of aes() specify which variables to map to the x- and y-axes.

  • An aesthetic is a visual property of the objects in your plot. Aesthetics include things like the size, the shape or the color of your points.

  • To map an aesthetic to a variable, associate the name of the aesthetic to the name of the variable inside aes().

  • ggplot2 will automatically assign a unique level of the aesthetic to each unique value of the variable , a process known as scaling.

  • ggplot2 will also add a legend that explains which levels correspond to which values.

install the ggplot2 package

install.packages(ggplot2) - run this command in Rstudio.

Scatter plots for paired data

A scatter plot provides a case-by-case view of data for two numerical variables. Scatterplots are one type of graph used to study the relationship between two numerical variables.

We will work with the data: births14

Loading data and the package

library(ggplot2)
births14=read.csv("births14 .csv")
births14=na.omit(births14) ## remove all NAs

Scatter plot for mage and fage using ggplot

ggplot(births14, aes(x=mage,y=fage))+geom_point(col="purple", shape=19, size=1.5)+ ggtitle("Scatter Plot between  mage and fage")+labs(x="Mother's age in years",y="Father's age in years")

Same plot in base R

x=births14$mage
y=births14$fage
plot(x,y, xlab= "Mothers age in years", ylab= "Fathers age in years",bty="n" ,pch=19,col="purple")

Histograms and shape

Histograms provide a view of the data density. Higher bars represent where the data are relatively more common.

  • The bars make it easy to see how the density of the data changes relative to the value of the variable
  • Histograms are especially convenient for understanding the shape of the data distribution.

When data trail of to the right in this way and has a longer right tail, the shape is said to be right skewed

Data sets with the reverse characteristic - a long, thinner tail to the left - are said to be left skewed.

We also say that such a distribution has a long left tail. Data sets that show roughly equal trailing of in both directions are called symmetric

Histogram for interest rate from loan50 data

Lets make histigram for fatghers age
ggplot(births14,aes(x= fage)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5,color="blue", fill="purple") + labs(x= "Fathers age in years", y="Frequency")+ ggtitle("Histogram of fage")

Histogram with density curve

ggplot(births14,aes(x= fage,y = ..density..)) + geom_histogram(binwidth = 5,color="blue", fill="purple") + labs(x= "Fathers age in years", y="Frequency")+ ggtitle("Histogram of fage")+ geom_density(col="red",size=1)

Considering categorical data

Contingency tables and bar plots

A contingency table is a tabular representation of categorical data . A contingency table usually shows frequencies for particular combinations of values of two discrete random variable s X and Y. Each cell in the table represents a mutually exclusive combination of X-Y values.

Contingency table for the variables sex and habit.

Gender=births14$sex
Habit=births14$habit
table(Gender, Habit)
##         Habit
## Gender   nonsmoker smoker
##   female       367     27
##   male         365     35
Gender=births14$sex
Habit=births14$habit
Gender_Habit=table( Habit,Gender)
Gender_Habit
##            Gender
## Habit       female male
##   nonsmoker    367  365
##   smoker        27   35

pie chart for the variable habit

x=table(births14$habit)
count=as.numeric(x)
names=names(x)
piepercent<- round(100*count/sum(count), 1)
pie(count,radius=1, labels = piepercent, main = "Pie chart for habit",col = rainbow(length(count)))
legend("topright", names, cex =1, fill = rainbow(length(count)))

ggplot2 does not offer any specific geom to build piecharts. We can use geom_bar() and coord_polar() for it.

x=table(births14$habit)
count=as.numeric(x)
names=names(x)
data <- data.frame(count,names)
# Basic piechart
ggplot(data, aes(x="", y=count, fill=names)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity", width=1, color="white") +
  coord_polar("y", start=0) + theme_void() # remove background, grid, numeric labels
